because, over <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">the last several years</TIMEX> and for several to come, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Social Security</ENAMEX>
payroll taxes have far exceeded, and will continue to far exceed, the benefits
paid out. Those surpluses, totaling <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">more than $1 trillion</NUMEX> by the end of this
<TIMEX TYPE="DATE">decade</TIMEX>, are supposed to be "invested" against the rainy day when the baby
boomers retire. Instead, they are simply transferred to the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Treasury</ENAMEX> in
exchange for IOUs (plus IOUs for interest on past loans). The money is then
used to help cover the costs of everything from <ENAMEX TYPE="EVENT">Black Hawk</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="PRODUCT_DESC">helicopters</ENAMEX> to <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">White</ENAMEX>
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">House</ENAMEX> spinners. <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Social Security</ENAMEX> is thus doing the rest of the budget--and --a
huge favor since, without its loans, the much touted budget surplus would be a
